Week 3 Exercise

Locating files in R

Download this zip file containing another example RNA-seq dataset:-

  • GSE100687.zip
  1. Create a New Rstudio project for this dataset

Recall the code that we used to read the data for the Fibroblast data.

library(tximport)
dirs <- list.files("salmon_quant/")
quant_files <- list.files("salmon_quant/",pattern="quant.sf.gz",recursive = TRUE,full.names = TRUE)
names(quant_files) <- dirs
txi <- tximport(quant_files,
                type="salmon",
                tx2gene = tx2gene,
                ignoreTxVersion = TRUE)

Exercise This code will not work on this new dataset. What changes do you need to make to the code to make it work?

  • the directory salmon_quant needs to be changed to salmon_output.
  • the pattern argument needs to be quant.sf

As we discovered in the practical, the tx2gene.csv file is used to aggregate the counts of different transcripts for the same gene. Follow the code below to read this file into R.

library(readr)

The full code to read the data is therefore

dirs <- list.files("salmon_output/")
quant_files <- list.files("salmon_output/",pattern="quant.sf",recursive = TRUE,full.names = TRUE)
names(quant_files) <- dirs
txi <- tximport(quant_files,
                type="salmon",
                tx2gene = tx2gene,
                ignoreTxVersion = TRUE)

Now, proceed to create a DESeq2 object for the dataset using the code below.

library(DESeq2)
dds <- DESeqDataSetFromTximport(txi,
                                colData = sampleInfo,
                                design = ~CellLine)

Exercise: - What is the total number of reads present for each sample? - Visualise the number of counts as a barplot, with different colours for each cell line and a horizontal line to indicate 3.5 million reads

sampleInfo %>% 
  mutate(libSize = colSums(counts(dds))/1e6) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = GSE, y = libSize,fill=CellLine)) + geom_col() + geom_hline(yintercept = 3.5)

Similar to the colSums function used in the previous exercise, there are also rowMeans and rowSums functions that can be applied to numerical matrices (such as the counts matrix).

Exercise: - What quantities are computed by applying the rowMeans and rowSums functions to the count matrix?

rowMeans(counts(dds))
rowSums(counts(dds))
  • How might the output of these functions be used to determine genes that are not expressed in our dataset?

rowMeans and rowSums give the average expression and total expression for each gene separately. Some workflows advocate removing genes with low expression in order to reduce the problem of multiple testing.

We can make a table of the rowSums output which will tell us how many genes are never sequenced:-

table(rowSums(counts(dds)))[1:10]


    0     1     2     3     4     5     6     7     8 
25440  4785  2435  1637  1117   916   766   571   554 
    9 
  457

Even though we have have over 50,000 rows in the data; nearly half of these are empty (zero counts) and will only add “noise” to our analysis

To visualise the means we can use a density plot on the log2 transformed values.

This shows a large number of genes have very small counts, and another peak around 7 (which is 128 on the raw scale). There is quite a long tail with some genes having average counts of around 2^15.

data.frame(Mean = rowMeans(counts(dds))) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = log2(Mean))) + geom_density()
